WEBVTT

00:00.322 --> 00:04.227
Today's reading is from John 6 starting at verse 1.

00:06.550 --> 00:20.449
Sometime after this, Jesus crossed to the far shore of the Sea of Galilee, and a great crowd of people followed him because they saw the signs he had performed by healing the sick.

00:21.550 --> 00:27.298
Then Jesus went up on the mountainside and sat down with his disciples.

00:28.259 --> 00:30.322
The Jewish Passover Festival

00:30.434 --> 00:30.995
was near.

00:31.915 --> 00:41.945
When Jesus looked up and saw a great crowd coming towards him, he said to Philip, where shall we buy bread for these people to eat?

00:42.846 --> 00:49.353
He asked this only to test him, for he already had in mind what he was going to do.

00:50.514 --> 00:58.642
Philip answered him, it would take more than a half a year's wage to buy enough bread for each one to have a bite.

00:59.650 --> 01:04.275
Another of his disciples, Andrew, Simon Peter's brother spoke up.

01:05.175 --> 01:10.301
Here is a boy with five small barley loaves and two small fish.

01:11.021 --> 01:14.104
But how far will they go among so many?

01:15.366 --> 01:18.228
Jesus said, have the people sit down?

01:18.849 --> 01:20.831
There was plenty of grass in that place.

01:22.292 --> 01:23.373
And they sat down.

01:24.414 --> 01:28.018
Jesus then took the loaves, gave thanks.

01:28.290 --> 01:30.913
and distributed to those who were seated.

01:31.774 --> 01:35.118
As much as they wanted, he did the same with the fish.

01:36.820 --> 01:46.152
When they had had all enough to eat, he said to his disciples, gather the pieces that are left over.

01:46.633 --> 01:48.335
Let nothing be wasted.

01:49.096 --> 01:57.586
So they gathered them and filled 12 baskets with the pieces of the five barley loaves left over by those who had eaten.

01:58.402 --> 02:01.406
After the people saw the sign, Jesus performed.

02:02.087 --> 02:08.035
They began to say, surely this is the prophet who is to come into the world.

02:08.756 --> 02:10.258
This is the word of the Lord.

02:16.426 --> 02:17.628
Good morning, foothills.

02:17.768 --> 02:18.709
Great to be with you.

02:19.290 --> 02:22.194
You know, whether it was the minus 28,

02:22.850 --> 02:31.502
or the December 28th, or the 28 people you might have staying in your home this time of year, you had reasons to not be here that were pretty valid.

02:31.943 --> 02:33.265
And thank you for being here.

02:33.325 --> 02:38.933
You know, this message I feel like God put on my heart actually months ago, so I'm very excited to share it.

02:40.054 --> 02:45.502
One of the first jobs that I ever had as a young man was working for college pro painting.

02:46.063 --> 02:51.410
Now, some of you I've painted your home since, so I've learned a few things here and there along the way.

02:51.522 --> 02:57.932
But when I started this job, a college pro, you have workers who are under regional supervisors.

02:58.513 --> 03:04.923
And our regional supervisor came to me as a worker and said, I've got a plan for how this summer's gonna go.

03:05.364 --> 03:10.171
We're gonna do all these quotes across all these towns in the area and we're gonna make this much money.

03:10.632 --> 03:12.976
And as workers, we thought, yes, we're gonna buy in.

03:13.396 --> 03:16.902
Your plan is going to become our purpose and we're gonna work hard.

03:17.703 --> 03:19.666
So we got assigned our very first job

03:20.418 --> 03:25.944
a century home with all kinds of windows that had these huge wooden shutters.

03:26.025 --> 03:31.431
And our job was to paint these wooden shutters with oil-based green paint.

03:32.172 --> 03:44.306
Now, when you're setting out in College Pro to make a lot of money in the summer, it would be safe to say that the objective is expediency and cost-cutting, not so much training.

03:45.090 --> 03:49.755
So the owner of the home comes out on our first day, and he strikes up a conversation with us.

03:49.815 --> 03:53.820
And he says, so what college do you guys go to?

03:53.840 --> 03:58.165
And we said, well, actually, the two of us are in grade 12.

03:59.667 --> 04:02.130
He said, well, how much experience do you have?

04:02.770 --> 04:05.013
We said, this is our first job.

04:06.294 --> 04:10.619
So with his confidence completely shaken, he said, so you're not really college pros.

04:10.659 --> 04:12.882
You're more like high school amateurs.

04:13.890 --> 04:25.101
And we proved him exactly right because on that first day, we grabbed the garden hose to wash the oil-based paint off our brushes and promptly stained his driveway green with the runoff.

04:26.102 --> 04:32.848
Let me tell you all the profit that our supervisor thought we would make that summer just got dissolved right then and there.

04:34.750 --> 04:42.898
Our supervisor might have had plans and we as workers might have said those plans will become our purpose, but we were out of our depth.

04:43.426 --> 04:52.996
Today, we're exploring this story from the Bible where Jesus had his plans and his plans had become the disciples' purpose, but they find themselves out of their depth.

04:54.918 --> 04:56.099
It's the final Sunday of 2025.

04:57.120 --> 04:57.941
You might be aware.

04:57.961 --> 05:04.588
The New Year's right around the corner, and this often brings a mix of emotions for all kinds of people, for all kinds of reasons.

05:05.449 --> 05:10.514
Maybe we're looking back and we're reflecting with gratitude, because amazing things happened in 2025.

05:11.618 --> 05:14.342
Maybe we experienced loss and so we're grieving.

05:15.043 --> 05:19.470
Some of us might be looking forward to 2026 with great excitement and anticipation.

05:20.091 --> 05:23.336
Others might feel very overwhelmed of what the new year will hold.

05:24.518 --> 05:27.282
And some will feel rested as you arrive at a new year.

05:28.003 --> 05:34.172
Others will feel a sense of exhaustion from parenting or work or uncertain to you or the pressures of life.

05:35.775 --> 05:38.098
You see, the new year has this unique way

05:38.690 --> 05:43.997
of revealing how the previous 365 days has gotten the better of us.

05:44.878 --> 05:49.744
It's one of the reasons why we make resolutions about how the next year's gonna be different.

05:51.226 --> 06:00.498
And as a church, you could say that we are actually about to make some New Year's resolutions ourselves because we're wrapping up our year of discernment.

06:01.138 --> 06:07.186
And in January, Pastor Kyle is going to bring a teaching series where we begin to unveil

06:07.426 --> 06:12.713
God's vision, mission, and values to guide our church into the future.

06:13.754 --> 06:16.458
And this too can bring some mixed emotions, can't it?

06:17.579 --> 06:21.605
For some of us, it's excitement and optimism of what God has in store.

06:22.125 --> 06:28.654
For others, we might look at it and feel this sense of our own limitations, or even the doubts that we bring to the table.

06:30.236 --> 06:34.802
And today's text is this famous story of Jesus feeding 5,000 people.

06:34.914 --> 06:37.077
And it too is a story of mixed emotions.

06:37.517 --> 06:45.328
It's where the disciples excitement from their first ministry journey comes up against their sense of limitations and exhaustion.

06:47.190 --> 06:49.293
And this is where Jesus ministers to them.

06:49.413 --> 06:52.818
And he works amidst all of this to reveal his plans.

06:54.019 --> 06:59.286
This is a story where God's plans become his people's purpose.

07:00.368 --> 07:01.970
And that's what we're going to look at today.

07:02.562 --> 07:13.175
And as we do, a little bit of a road map for our time together is we're going to find that when God's plans become his people's purpose, the spent are sustained.

07:14.456 --> 07:19.102
The problem meets perspective and the meager gets multiplied.

07:20.083 --> 07:20.543
Let's pray.

07:23.347 --> 07:29.714
Jesus, as we open your word today together, would you open our hearts to receive what you would say to us?

07:30.882 --> 07:35.507
Where we come into today feeling spent, would you sustain us?

07:35.527 --> 07:39.891
And where we feel overwhelmed by problems, would you give us your perspective?

07:41.012 --> 07:47.739
And where we feel like we have so little to offer, would you show us what you can do with a surrendered life?

07:49.300 --> 07:59.090
And for those exploring faith today, Jesus helped them to hear your invitation to a life of purpose according to your will

08:00.066 --> 08:06.537
And to those of us who are following you, help us to be obedient to what you have to say to us today.

08:07.198 --> 08:08.380
We pray this in Jesus' name.

08:08.920 --> 08:09.201
Amen.

08:11.364 --> 08:16.072
Let's take a look at some of the context that surrounds this unique passage of Scripture.

08:16.813 --> 08:24.626
The story of Jesus feeding the 5,000 is actually the only miracle that appears in all four gospels other than the resurrection of Christ.

08:25.090 --> 08:29.194
And all four of the gospel authors capture unique details.

08:29.254 --> 08:39.383
And so as much as John 6 is going to be our primary text today, I'm gonna pull from some of the others as well because it helps to round out the story and give us our applications for today.

08:40.685 --> 08:48.052
So this miracle happens at what you might call a critical juncture or an inflection point in Jesus' earthly ministry.

08:48.992 --> 08:54.898
His fame is spread widely, the crowds are growing rapidly, and opposition from religious leaders

08:55.010 --> 09:04.304
is growing and intensifying and the disciples have just come back from their first being sent out by Jesus to do the work of his ministry.

09:05.126 --> 09:12.477
So the first thing that we actually see in Mark chapter six, where he accounts for this, is that the disciples are tired.

09:13.058 --> 09:20.389
They are spent from this going out around the countryside and serving countless people in the name of Jesus.

09:20.409 --> 09:23.634
Mark tells us that when they arrive at this instance,

09:23.970 --> 09:26.835
they have not even had anything to eat themselves.

09:27.556 --> 09:31.082
So they are physically, emotionally, and spiritually drained at this point.

09:31.783 --> 09:37.151
And now there's a hungry crowd of thousands of people following them around the countryside.

09:37.852 --> 09:42.200
So they're both tired and now overwhelmed by the pressure.

09:43.562 --> 09:48.690
At the same time, John says in chapter six, this important detail.

09:49.538 --> 09:54.043
Jesus already had in mind what he was going to do about this whole situation.

09:55.224 --> 10:04.493
And it's this juxtaposition of Jesus having plans and the disciples having a purpose that makes our application for us today.

10:05.074 --> 10:12.201
And the first thing that we find here is that when God's plans become his people's purpose, the spent are sustained.

10:14.664 --> 10:17.106
When my three daughters were five, three, and one,

10:18.050 --> 10:25.498
Our parents, my parents in law, who happen to be in the room today, graciously gifted us a family Caribbean cruise.

10:26.539 --> 10:27.981
And we got really excited.

10:28.502 --> 10:30.964
We're thinking, let's go be so restful.

10:31.004 --> 10:33.627
We'll be lounging around on the deck all day in the sun.

10:35.729 --> 10:42.337
And as all of your giggling suggests, you're on to what I'm getting at with a five, three, and one year old.

10:42.517 --> 10:44.779
It was not what we thought it would be.

10:44.819 --> 10:47.122
For these reasons,

10:47.586 --> 11:02.448
Two of our two youngest daughters weren't old enough for the onboard childcare, so off-ship excursions out of the question, and my wife and I had a bedtime now of 7 p.m. That's when we had to be in our cabin.

11:03.309 --> 11:12.402
What's more, our baby wasn't allowed in any of the pools, and all the doors open automatically for our walking three and five-year-olds.

11:12.834 --> 11:19.981
So we are constantly doing split defense parenting, head on a swivel all the time, and to top it all off.

11:20.902 --> 11:34.495
It seemed that every single person who was on that cruise ship had either never seen or was related to a red head, which meant that every elevator conversation was about my daughter's red hair.

11:35.616 --> 11:42.322
So we were very quickly more exhausted than we had if we had just stayed home.

11:42.946 --> 11:43.887
Why do I say this?

11:44.027 --> 11:51.174
Well, there came a point in this journey where the frustration was real, and I'm sure I was quite grumpy.

11:51.575 --> 11:53.116
I'm sure my wife would attest to it.

11:53.677 --> 12:05.949
But my parents-in-law, without owing us anything and with great understanding and compassion, took the kids for a night and let us have a date night where we could rest and recover our strength.

12:07.010 --> 12:10.514
They sustained us when we were spent

12:11.138 --> 12:21.913
And Jesus, not owing his disciples anything in this text, and without any judgment, sustains his disciples in two ways that we see revealed here.

12:23.335 --> 12:39.058
Mark's account tells us that the disciples had excitedly set out on this mission that Jesus had given them, and they had now returned and they're glorifying God for all that he had done in them and through them, but do in part to the disciples' work

12:39.394 --> 12:49.266
And the expanding of the message of Jesus through the countryside, they are now followed around by this huge crowd that is relentlessly pursuing Jesus.

12:49.887 --> 12:58.017
These are people who have heard about Jesus and they've seen his miraculous signs and they've come seeking what he might have in store for them.

13:00.320 --> 13:07.008
And so the pressure of carrying for all these needy people was getting to the disciples.

13:07.729 --> 13:08.690
They were spent.

13:10.050 --> 13:13.836
But Jesus doesn't rebuke the disciples for their exhaustion.

13:14.557 --> 13:16.781
He doesn't shame them for needing rest here.

13:17.902 --> 13:20.286
Instead, he invites them into solitude and retreat.

13:21.007 --> 13:24.993
He says, come with me by yourselves to a quiet place and get some rest.

13:27.918 --> 13:33.367
For some of us, that's the invitation that we need to hear from Jesus as we head into a new year.

13:34.408 --> 13:35.570
Come and get some rest.

13:36.546 --> 13:40.831
Because this is the counterpoint to the way that many of us tend to live our lives with Jesus.

13:40.891 --> 13:41.712
Myself included.

13:41.772 --> 13:43.855
This is a struggling point for me as well.

13:44.736 --> 13:52.605
Because we're prone to mistakenly attaching our worth and value in the eyes of God to what we can produce for him.

13:54.107 --> 13:56.330
The stuff that we can do for the kingdom.

13:57.071 --> 13:59.634
And this leads us to live lives as though

13:59.810 --> 14:09.339
Following Jesus means endlessly expending ourselves for his purposes, even to the point of some sort of righteous exhaustion.

14:12.523 --> 14:16.326
The problem with this is that Jesus exemplified exactly the opposite.

14:18.048 --> 14:28.178
He would retreat to quiet places to pray and be away from the crowds and be in the presence of his father and leave the demands of life and of people behind.

14:28.610 --> 14:32.174
He prioritized space for mental and physical rest.

14:32.935 --> 14:35.497
And so can I get an amen to taking naps?

14:36.258 --> 14:37.560
Like that's what I'm all about.

14:37.580 --> 14:43.346
I often will tell people I will go away to retreat centers and just have a nap.

14:43.366 --> 14:45.348
And to the glory of God, it's wonderful.

14:46.709 --> 14:52.456
Furthermore, we see in this passage that he invites his followers into these practices too.

14:54.738 --> 14:57.561
So the first way that Jesus sustains his followers is through rest.

14:57.601 --> 14:58.482
And the second,

14:58.658 --> 15:01.342
is through nourishment.

15:01.362 --> 15:15.062
What really caught my attention when I was going through this passage, something that had never caught me before, was how the disciples had been so consumed with the work of ministry that they arrive here, having not even eaten themselves.

15:15.423 --> 15:17.786
They are as famished as the crowd.

15:18.107 --> 15:25.618
And admittedly, I'd never caught that before because I've only ever focused on the lens of what must this miracle have meant for the crowd.

15:28.098 --> 15:33.724
This is a glimpse given to us of what it meant for the disciples, for Jesus' followers.

15:35.446 --> 15:45.696
Jesus miraculously sustained them too, and so abundantly that all 12 of them walk away with personal baskets of leftovers at the end.

15:46.938 --> 15:54.866
But the lesson for the disciples here, and the lesson for us, isn't that Jesus is gonna come through in the clutch with the Snickers bar when you're not yourself?

15:56.034 --> 15:58.518
It's not about physical nourishment here.

15:59.119 --> 16:03.706
This is about a reminder that Jesus is the nourishment for the soul.

16:05.348 --> 16:11.117
And like the disciples in the story, every Christian is called to serve the purposes of God.

16:12.139 --> 16:16.626
As the Holy Spirit transforms us, we actually become people who we want to.

16:17.026 --> 16:26.439
We're thrilled to go out and do the work of ministry on Jesus behalf, but we do so in a world where the pressure of need is always there.

16:29.122 --> 16:39.636
It will always demand of our time and our resources and our energy and of our mental and physical well-being and not to mention the spiritual warfare attached to it.

16:40.037 --> 16:47.026
Jesus knew that more often than not, it would not be our stomachs that grow hungry from the work of ministry

16:47.554 --> 16:53.660
And he invites us into the life-giving rhythms of rest and into a reminder of his all-sufficiency.

16:53.700 --> 17:02.048
Because when his plans become our purpose, it's our souls that most need nourishment.

17:06.312 --> 17:07.794
And maybe you're a follower of Jesus.

17:09.115 --> 17:16.402
And you've come here today and you've walked into the church feeling spent from a year's worth of

17:16.578 --> 17:25.208
ministry, and the demands of life, and high output caring for the needs of others, your family, even yourself.

17:26.710 --> 17:36.521
And as you look to the year ahead, you need that reminder that when God's plans become your purpose, the spend are sustained.

17:39.805 --> 17:40.946
On the other hand, maybe

17:41.090 --> 17:49.879
You've entered our doors here today, or you're joining us online, and you can't relate at all to the disciples in the story, but you can relate to the crowd.

17:51.461 --> 17:53.963
There's a spiritual hunger that you are experiencing.

17:55.165 --> 18:04.114
And you've heard stories, or you've seen something different in the life of a Christian, or you've caught a glimpse of what Jesus can do.

18:04.654 --> 18:08.178
And you've come saying, I wonder what he has for me.

18:11.682 --> 18:22.181
what Jesus has for you is spiritual nourishment, the likes of which you can't imagine, to satisfy every of your spiritual needs, the desires of your soul.

18:23.804 --> 18:26.549
And so if that's you today, you've come to the right person.

18:28.813 --> 18:33.682
And my encouragement to you, will you receive what he has to offer you?

18:38.242 --> 18:45.351
The second point that we can take away from this text is that when God's plans become his people's purpose, the problem meets perspective.

18:46.732 --> 18:48.675
I love telling this story, a friend of mine.

18:48.695 --> 18:53.621
He once tried to save some money by doing his own break job on his car.

18:54.502 --> 18:57.866
Some of you immediately are relating to this story for a better or for worse.

18:58.867 --> 18:59.788
And I can as well.

19:00.809 --> 19:02.231
So here's how this story went for him.

19:03.232 --> 19:08.018
He got the tire off, he got the brake caliper off, but then he quickly discovered that his

19:08.162 --> 19:12.387
Brake rotor was so rusted, it was as though it had been welded on.

19:13.629 --> 19:20.497
So he reassembled everything on his car and he drove to the store and he bought some penetrating oil thinking if I spray this on, that's gonna loosen it, it'll work.

19:21.158 --> 19:21.619
Didn't work.

19:22.460 --> 19:29.949
So he did some research, reassembled his car again, drove to the store a second time, purchased a torch thinking heat's gonna get this thing off.

19:30.650 --> 19:31.050
It didn't.

19:32.032 --> 19:34.615
Then came the hammer, brute force, okay?

19:35.015 --> 19:37.138
He is hammering away at the brake rotor.

19:37.378 --> 19:54.536
Now he's damaged it so badly that he can't drive back to the store, has to borrow a friend's car, drives back to the store a third time to purchase a sledgehammer, comes back to his garage, is wailing on this thing until soon pieces of brake rotor are all over his garage.

19:54.556 --> 20:04.786
And finally in great dismay, four hours in to the first wheel of this brake job, he calls up a friend and his friend comes over and he takes a look at the situation.

20:05.698 --> 20:10.785
And he says, would anyone in this situation would simultaneously love and hate to hear?

20:10.845 --> 20:12.747
Well, there's your problem.

20:14.089 --> 20:23.221
You see, hidden under the rust were these two little things called retaining screws that once removed, the rotor just slid right off.

20:26.546 --> 20:27.367
Perspective.

20:29.530 --> 20:31.653
The problem just needed a little perspective.

20:32.394 --> 20:35.698
And the disciples in this story, they saw the problem.

20:36.290 --> 20:38.994
and they needed a divine perspective from Jesus.

20:39.775 --> 20:47.025
You see, they were secluded in the wilderness, and they made a point of mentioning this, and it's late in the day, and the disciples suggested Jesus.

20:47.947 --> 20:51.952
The best solution right now, just send this crowd away, Jesus.

20:53.795 --> 20:57.540
But Jesus says to them something very interesting in Mark 6.

20:59.062 --> 21:01.586
He says, you give them something to eat.

21:04.962 --> 21:09.989
And in John 6 it records that he says to Philip, where shall we buy bread for all of these people?

21:11.050 --> 21:13.153
And Philip protests, obviously.

21:13.213 --> 21:19.041
He says it would take more than half a year's wages to buy this much bread to give everyone even one bite.

21:20.924 --> 21:25.630
And so the understandably stunned disciples agree that the best course of action is actually Jesus.

21:25.971 --> 21:29.796
Let's send them to all the towns throughout the countryside where they can buy their own bread.

21:30.557 --> 21:34.162
We certainly can't afford to do this.

21:34.786 --> 22:02.834
Besides the obvious, I had to ask this question of this text, why is it that suddenly now, after having just returned from their missionary journey, after having been used by God to heal sick people and cast out demons and work miracles in Jesus' name, when Jesus said, feed some people, the disciples choose that moment to say, whoa, whoa, I can't be used in that kind of a way.

22:04.066 --> 22:09.373
And I think that there's three hang-ups here that the disciples have, which are pretty common hang-ups for all of us.

22:11.095 --> 22:12.276
And they could be summed up this way.

22:13.357 --> 22:18.524
Forgetful, this was a first, and their focus was wrong.

22:20.566 --> 22:21.668
The disciples were forgetful.

22:21.868 --> 22:33.202
This is inescapable from the text, because at this point, in their relationship with Jesus, the disciples must have lost sight of at least some of the things that Jesus had done up to this point.

22:33.474 --> 22:47.516
Because prior to this, they have witnessed him produce a miraculous catch of fish, turn water into wine, calm a storm with his words, heal multiple people, and even raise a dead person, which brings us to the second hangup.

22:48.517 --> 22:51.362
This was the first time they'd ever considered a miracle like this.

22:52.644 --> 22:59.314
And maybe their reluctance was precisely because they'd never seen this miracle before.

23:01.570 --> 23:04.455
Even Jesus hadn't fed thousands of people yet.

23:06.438 --> 23:08.260
And third, their focus was all wrong.

23:09.542 --> 23:16.113
It's evident from every account of the four gospels that the disciples' focus was strictly on the problem.

23:16.553 --> 23:25.608
We're tired, there's too many people, it's a secluded place, it's late in the day, everybody's hungry, and on the limitations of human response to the problem.

23:26.269 --> 23:28.412
Send them away, let them buy their own food.

23:28.512 --> 23:29.714
We can't afford this.

23:31.010 --> 23:45.474
The disciples focus was on the problem and they needed a perspective shift that Jesus was going to bring because Jesus wasn't asking them for logistics and for strategy here, he was cultivating faith.

23:48.740 --> 23:57.394
You see, John tells us he asked this only to test them for Jesus already had in mind what he was going to do.

23:59.810 --> 24:07.517
Jesus was intentionally reshaping the perspective of the disciples into the perspective of God in the situation.

24:08.358 --> 24:16.286
And Jesus had a plan all along, and that's when it became clear to the disciples that Jesus was introducing them to God's perspective.

24:17.107 --> 24:21.591
And this is how Jesus disciples all of us as his people.

24:23.013 --> 24:28.658
He will actually bring us to places where our resources run out.

24:29.858 --> 24:35.308
in order that we would more fully see his perspective on the situation.

24:38.675 --> 24:50.898
As a church, we've been seeking God for our organizational vision, mission, and values that are going to carry us to 2033, 2000 years since the resurrection of Christ.

24:51.650 --> 25:03.027
And next Sunday, as Pastor Kyle begins to just scratch the surface of the audacious vision that God is revealing to us as a church, will we be like the disciples in this story?

25:06.493 --> 25:11.861
Will we forget all that he's done in the 60-year history of this church?

25:13.864 --> 25:17.970
Or will we shrink back from it because we've never seen him do that before?

25:20.738 --> 25:28.365
Or will our focus stay strictly on the human reasons why that's impossible and this is a problem and it won't work?

25:30.547 --> 25:42.359
Or by God's grace, will we embrace God's perspective and trust Him to do the miraculous and do it through us?

25:46.763 --> 25:50.226
Maybe your application is more towards the heart of an individual

25:50.498 --> 26:02.456
What if the problem that you see right now in life, in your family, in your workplace, in the world around you, your relationships, society in general, perhaps even in this church?

26:02.477 --> 26:07.965
What if those problems are actually invitations into God's perspective?

26:10.589 --> 26:18.962
What if the impossibility that you see is the canvas upon which God intends to reveal His plans for you?

26:24.322 --> 26:31.048
Because when God's plan becomes people's purpose, the problem meets perspective.

26:31.989 --> 26:37.375
And maybe as this year comes to its close, the pressures of life have brought you to the end of yourself.

26:40.297 --> 26:47.224
Maybe you've come to realize that your best efforts aren't enough to change your circumstances, much less your eternal destiny.

26:49.987 --> 26:53.330
And the good news is that Jesus already had in mind

26:53.986 --> 26:56.309
what he would do for you.

26:58.712 --> 27:13.910
He lived a sinless life, one that you could never live, and he died to pay the penalty you could never pay, so that God's plans could get realized in your life's purpose, including the plan for your eternal salvation.

27:18.315 --> 27:23.922
Now the final lesson that we can take away from this text is that when God's plans become his people's purpose,

27:24.450 --> 27:26.092
The meager gets multiplied.

27:27.433 --> 27:34.140
Now, 10 years ago, as a youth pastor, I began empowering young people to lead the Alpha course in their high schools.

27:34.240 --> 27:39.746
And if you don't know what the Alpha course is, it's a multi-week course that is an introduction to the Christian faith.

27:41.348 --> 27:48.436
And in the first year of doing this, we had five teams of students launch in five high schools, and we thought that that was pretty miraculous.

27:49.837 --> 27:54.322
And shortly thereafter, a young man came to me and he said, I want to start one in my middle school.

27:54.978 --> 27:57.000
And I had a bunch of problems with this.

27:57.961 --> 28:03.546
You see, the school had never had a Christian club to begin with, so we'd be setting out from scratch.

28:03.566 --> 28:08.791
Middle schools in general are pretty resistant to having any kind of Christian or religious club for that matter.

28:09.592 --> 28:13.796
This young man was only grade eight, and he was a lot like me in middle school.

28:14.236 --> 28:17.719
But Giki, not the most influential, and he was going solo.

28:17.859 --> 28:19.621
It was just him who wanted to do this.

28:21.483 --> 28:24.946
But a few weeks in to him running this course, he came to me and he said,

28:25.442 --> 28:28.365
Can I get some Bibles to hand out to the people coming to my Alpha?

28:29.487 --> 28:31.729
And I said to him, sure, how many did you need?

28:32.811 --> 28:33.892
He said 70.

28:36.535 --> 28:39.619
He had 70 middle schoolers coming through his Alpha.

28:40.420 --> 28:44.064
His meager offering got in multiply.

28:45.546 --> 28:47.107
And that's what we see here in John 6.

28:47.528 --> 28:52.754
John's the only one who captures this interaction with this unnamed little boy.

28:52.930 --> 28:59.298
Andrew enters the narrative, one of the disciples saying, here's this boy with five small barley loaves and two small fish.

29:00.479 --> 29:06.887
And John the author is intentionally capturing just how meager this offering is.

29:07.308 --> 29:12.835
Not only does he say the word small twice, but barley loave, that's the bread of the poor people.

29:13.415 --> 29:15.318
The fish were likely dried and pickled.

29:15.378 --> 29:17.621
This was not some nice salmon fillet.

29:18.422 --> 29:22.066
And the boy goes unnamed because he's seemingly insignificant.

29:23.458 --> 29:24.940
This was not an impressive gift.

29:25.360 --> 29:27.383
It wasn't strategic or scalable.

29:28.164 --> 29:31.748
It wasn't enough.

29:31.768 --> 29:38.437
So Andrew says what all the other disciples are thinking, but how far will this go among so many?

29:39.959 --> 29:43.123
And he reveals the disciples have an underlying assumption.

29:44.785 --> 29:48.609
And it's this, that God's work depends on human adequacy.

29:50.432 --> 29:52.274
And Jesus is about to dismantle.

29:52.354 --> 29:53.675
that assumption entirely.

29:58.281 --> 30:02.425
Jesus doesn't go to the boy and say, we're going to need some more from you, son.

30:04.167 --> 30:07.531
He doesn't belittle this boy for the size of the offering.

30:09.013 --> 30:11.015
He doesn't wait until there is enough.

30:12.717 --> 30:17.522
Jesus receives what is surrendered, and that's where the miracle begins.

30:19.650 --> 30:25.276
The miracle here isn't just provision, it's participation.

30:28.880 --> 30:32.624
Jesus could have created bread out of thin air like that.

30:33.645 --> 30:36.468
He'd proven that much and more at this point in his ministry.

30:37.029 --> 30:39.972
But instead he chose to involve the disciples.

30:41.233 --> 30:41.493
Why?

30:44.356 --> 30:49.522
Because the point of this miracle wasn't just feeding the crowd, it was forming his followers.

30:50.914 --> 31:07.298
The miracle taught the disciples that God does not wait for abundance before He acts, and God delights in obedience more than adequacy, and God's power is revealed precisely where human resources come to their end.

31:08.880 --> 31:14.589
And all four of the Gospels say they all ate and were satisfied.

31:16.892 --> 31:20.818
What the disciples thought was insufficient, what they nearly dismissed,

31:20.898 --> 31:27.348
what seemed pointless even to offer in the first place Jesus multiplied into abundance.

31:31.455 --> 31:41.511
As we step into a new vision as a church, this moment from the story should maybe resonate deeply with those of us who can relate to this unnamed boy in this story.

31:42.152 --> 31:48.562
Maybe we feel like our offering is insufficient and it's pointlessly offered.

31:49.442 --> 32:03.060
because we're spiritually underqualified or we're emotionally drained or we're relationally stretched thin or we're wounded or financial limitations or we're unsure if we've got anything at all that would matter to God.

32:03.801 --> 32:07.947
And Jesus doesn't say to you, come back when you've got more.

32:13.875 --> 32:18.962
He says, bring me your meager offering and watch me multiply it.

32:20.002 --> 32:21.644
beyond your wildest imagination.

32:26.308 --> 32:27.729
So you can bring your little faith.

32:32.554 --> 32:34.316
You can bring your hesitant obedience.

32:35.136 --> 32:49.490
You can bring your small financial gift, your imperfect character, the spiritual gift you think is insignificant in the grand scheme of things, because when God's plans become His people's purpose, the meager

32:50.594 --> 32:56.203
gets multiplied.

32:56.223 --> 33:08.284
This unique and miraculous story, it teaches us something very vital about how God works through his church, which is that God rarely starts with what looks sufficient.

33:10.607 --> 33:13.072
He starts with what is surrendered to him.

33:15.075 --> 33:16.978
The future God is calling foothills into

33:19.074 --> 33:25.482
won't be accomplished by our size or our strength or our strategy.

33:26.824 --> 33:33.212
It's going to be fueled by faithful obedience and surrendered availability and trust in Jesus' sufficiency.

33:36.556 --> 33:40.160
So allow me to put a very practical challenge in front of you.

33:41.702 --> 33:44.786
As we enter a season of a new vision and mission for our church,

33:48.706 --> 33:55.214
we should no longer see pray first events of 20 to 30 people.

33:58.839 --> 34:17.522
Let's see hundreds or the thousands of us gathering to surrender what we have and bring great expectation for how God will work miraculously through us because the miracle is never what we have to offer.

34:17.730 --> 34:19.212
It's what Jesus does with it.

34:22.515 --> 34:25.899
And that's not just true for churches, it's true for lives.

34:27.581 --> 34:34.969
Because the greatest multiplication in this story is not bread in the hands of people, it's grace in the hands of Christ.

34:36.111 --> 34:42.578
So if you're exploring faith and maybe for whatever reason the New Year has brought you to coming to church,

34:43.874 --> 34:47.698
You might feel like you've got nothing of significance to bring to Jesus.

34:48.759 --> 34:51.062
You're not impressive, you're not spiritual.

34:52.103 --> 34:53.985
You would feel like you don't matter to God.

34:54.746 --> 35:04.537
But the miracle of this story reveals that Jesus multiplies what is surrendered to him and he invites you to surrender your life and see it multiplied in its purpose.

35:05.277 --> 35:09.262
He already knows what he intends to do with you.

35:09.882 --> 35:13.266
He already knows the purpose he has for your story.

35:13.634 --> 35:16.898
And he already knows the plans for your eternity.

35:19.101 --> 35:20.563
Will you trust him today?

35:22.586 --> 35:24.909
Will you place your life in his hands?

35:28.054 --> 35:31.639
Will you receive the bread of life that satisfies the hunger of the soul?

35:33.541 --> 35:38.187
Because this miracle does more than talk about filling empty stomachs.

35:38.268 --> 35:42.994
It points to a Savior that fills empty hearts and still does.

35:44.866 --> 35:48.811
Jesus is not only the one who multiplies the bread, he is the bread.

35:49.312 --> 35:51.896
He spoke of himself as the bread of life.

35:52.316 --> 35:54.900
He's the one broken and the one given for us.

35:55.480 --> 36:04.092
He's the one who sustains the spend and who brings perspective to the problem and multiplies our meager offerings.

36:05.214 --> 36:11.442
So as we enter 2026, let's offer him what we have.

36:12.866 --> 36:18.513
Let's trust him for what we don't have and let's step into his purposes together.

36:21.277 --> 36:22.218
Would you join me in prayer?

36:27.425 --> 36:40.082
Jesus, thank you for sustaining the spent and for reshaping our perspective when problems overwhelm us and for multiplying what little we bring.

36:41.986 --> 36:51.059
Would you take our lives, our gifts, our time, our faith, our obedience, and use them for your glorious purposes?

36:52.902 --> 36:54.725
Make our plans your purpose.

36:56.527 --> 37:04.720
For our church, make your vision our calling, and make our heart your pursuit.

37:06.362 --> 37:09.106
In the name of Jesus we pray, amen.

